choices.text:
The patient has a history of a gunshot wound to the right thigh five years ago, with current symptoms including a buzzing sensation near the scar, a loud murmur with a thrill, and dilated varicose veins with incompetent valves in the lower leg. These findings are highly suggestive of an arteriovenous (AV) fistula, which can result from trauma such as a gunshot wound. Over time, an AV fistula can lead to abnormal communication between an artery and a vein, resulting in increased blood flow into the venous system, causing a murmur and thrill due to turbulent blood flow. The presence of varicose veins and valve incompetence is a classic consequence of chronic venous hypertension due to AV fistulae.

While arterial spasm (A) or occlusion of the superficial femoral artery (D) could be considered in some vascular contexts, they do not typically produce a murmur with thrill and associated venous dilation and incompetence. Deep venous thrombosis (C) would present with pain, swelling, and possibly a positive Homan’s sign, not a thrill or murmur. Arteriovenous fistula (B) best explains the combination of findings.

The answer is (B)

Question: Five years after being shot in the right thigh, a 21-year-old man comes to the emergency department because of a buzzing sensation adjacent to the scar. At the time of the initial wound, he was discharged after 6 hours of observation with no fractures or soft-tissue swelling. A loud murmur is heard on auscultation; there is a thrill. He has dilated varicose veins with incompetent valves in the lower leg. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?
